social_posts.post_text: I am on a roll with training, but this week there is so much snow in the forecast that may deter my plans. I always end up injured when I run through the snow and I despise the treadmill. Luckily, I'm much more flexible now than when I was younger and am able to go with the proverbial meteorological flow.

It was an honor to speak at the @wildwoodrunningpdx clinic this weekend in Portland, Oregon. On Saturday I got to talk to an amazing group of coaches who were open and willing to get curious about the beliefs and thoughts they hold about health and nutrition and how their behaviors are personally influenced. Then on Sunday, I had a moving discussion with the young athletes on their feelings and emotions around food and what it means to be healthy (spoiler alert: everybody's definition is different), and how that affects their relationship with food and their bodies. 
I'm taking away from this experience new connections, new ideas and new inspiration for the future.

It's always hard to narrow down the most memorable adventures of the year, but these stick out as top 5:

1. Annual Mt St Helens circumnavigation (go to reels).
2. PCT via Snoqualmie Pass during the Cascade Crest 100 (go to reels).
3. Grand Col Ferret, CCC course preview (pictured and a reel).
4. Snowy Lakes in the fall via Rainey Pass, PCT (go to reels).
5. Mt Rainier with no people and no smoke in October (pictured and a reel). 

Incredibly grateful for the support of @lasportivana,  @trailbutter,  @ultimatedirectionusa, @terraingym, Align Chiropractic, Active Points Wellness and @lilytrotters in 2022.

Ten Years.

When I went to choose a running shoe company to partner with I wanted a brand that exemplified the entire outdoor experience and was environmentally aware. A company that made not just mountain and trail-specific running shoes, but also apparel. A small company vibe steadfast in their values. I'm grateful that 2023 marks 10 years that I will be on the La Sportiva Mountain Running Team. La Sportiva takes pride in their products and I'm proud to continue representing them on and off the trails.

I get to race on Saturday! This will be my fourth time racing on Orcas Island, but my first time running @rainshadowrunning's 50k. My last race in September feels like forever ago so I'm excited to pin on a bib and get after the 8,500 feet of gain over one of the most beautiful places in Washington. Please let me know if you'll be there, too!

My feelings about the Orcas Island 50km can best be summarized as delighted, confident, and grateful. 

Delighted because it was one of the days where everything just clicked. The weather was perfect for running, my body had no tightness or pain, and I had no anxiety holding me back. 

Confident because I got confirmation that my training over the last 5 months is working. I spend a lot of time grinding out long solo trail tempo runs that are challenging both mentally and physically. The way I felt running this race validates my work.

Grateful because Orcas Island is stunning. I got to share 17 magical miles with @rachelraedrake; her company and spirit propelling us forward. I'm grateful for everybody who came to cheer (especially @ksayler2 and @csayler), and I'm grateful for my fellow runners out there on the course with me. I'm grateful for the volunteers and the entire Rainshadow Running Team. James keeps the pure, unadulterated essence of trail races alive. I'm grateful to Tad for supporting me and being the most amazing crew person, documenting along the way. (For Tad's race day take-over, see Orcas 50km 2023 saved in my highlights reel.)

Bearing no interruptions or unforeseen circumstances, my 2023 race calendar is as follows:

Yakima Skyline Rim 50km - April @rainshadowrunning

Tiger Claw 50km - May
@runtigerclaw

Lavaredo 80km - June
@lavaredoultratrail

Backcountry Rise 50km - August
@daybreakracing

Fall races tbd

2023 support: @lasportivana, @trailbutter, @terraingym

I want to pass on all my good race feels to everybody running the Orcas Island 100 this weekend. May you be touched by the magic of the island.
Special well wishes to @alse3, @k__bird, @joelgartenberg, @christof.teuscher and @booch82 👏👏👏

My topic for group sessions this month is focusing on one of the most misunderstood emotions, anger. Anger is tricky because it is often seen as a "bad" emotion or it has been coupled with something negative or dangerous. But anger is actually incredibly important and necessary to express when it comes to healing our relationship with ourselves and our bodies, food and nourishment, and even relationships with other people. Anger maintains our sense of self, our boundaries and our values. If you learned to suppress or restrain your anger to keep yourself safe, I see you.
First workout back after the @rainshadowrunning Orcas 50k. 8 x 5min up with 1min down recovery. I felt good with no lingering fatigue. Ready to get back to work!

Don't try this in your shoes.
@lasportivana Blizzard GTX 🤘

I had the pleasure of sitting down over coffee with Josh and Mike from @thecafestopshow.* Josh and Mike are from the biking world so we talked about what makes the mountain ultra trail running world so special and then I geeked out on Polyvagal Theory and how I use it when working with my clients from a trauma-informed lens. A direct link to listen can be found in my profile. 

*Each episode is sponsored by the guest's favorite cafe and I chose the @mazamastore ❤️ 🥖

Food is relational, emotional, and safety-seeking. 

You might not realize it, but food issues happen in relationship so they can only be healed in relationship. How have your early attachment experiences impacted how you get your needs met?

Emotions help us live an embodied and relational life. You're going to have to feel to heal so how can we start to make space for that?

Eating difficulties is feeling like food and the body is a threat. Eating "healthy" can be an attempt at connection, acceptance or success; to be seen as worthy, valuable or enough. It's a valiant effort to feel safe. How can we start to orient to true safety and recognize what that feels like inside?

To learn more and set up a discovery call, please visit https://www.mariadalzotrd.com/schedule.

I just finished one of the best 8 week training blocks I've had going into an ultra. Regardless of the race in 11 days, it feels really good to have this work under my belt and I'm proud of it. There have been hundreds of races where my training was stalled from injuries, weather, life stress, etc. So, when the stars align and I get uninterrupted quality time, I'm going to celebrate that accomplishment.

Part 1: Course preview of the southern half of the Yakima Skyline Rim Trail. The 50k is April 15th!

@rainshadowrunning
Part 2: Course preview of the Northern half of the Yakima Skyline Rim Trail. Fingers crossed for no crazy wind on race day!

I am going to channel my grandma's strength, tenacity and perseverance while racing tomorrow. She was a tough cookie and got really upset when you didn't eat enough so I like to think I take after her. This one's for you, Grandma.

At the start line of the @rainshadowrunning Yakima Skyline 50k, James asked everyone, "Are you ready to suffer!? If not, you are in the wrong place." Well I was definitely in the right place because suffer is what I did. 
I went into this race having high expectations and my eye on the course record. @stacemarion and I were 1 minute over @kaytlyn_g 's smokin fast time at 8 miles and just two minutes over at halfway. As I headed up the third climb, I started feeling really off. It quickly turned into really bad nausea. It was like I suddenly had the flu. From 17 miles to the finish it was a sufferfest, bending over to dry heave and vomit the final 8 miles. Everybody who passed me was so nice to me, I want to thank each of you personally. Maybe this race deserves a blog post. It's funny how there are so many more stories for the shitty races. I'm okay now and don't know what happened other than I started my period that morning. Thank you all for your love and support, congrats to Stacey for taking the W, and thank you to all of the volunteers out there helping us do this wild sport. I announced my retirement at the finish line, but perhaps that was an impulsive emotional decision.
Pro Tip: don't puke into the wind ✌️

(Tad's takeover is saved in my highlight reels under 'Yakima 50k'. He did a great job despite limited access to the course and poor cell service.)

Next month while Tad and I are in Europe, we are going to fastpack the UTMB course over 5 days. Training with a much heavier pack has been a fun new albeit challenging experience. I'm sore in weird little places despite going to the gym three times a week for ten years.
Still grinding away with less than a month away from Lavaredo. The snow levels are still very low, but slowly creeping up.

It's June! As much as I love the not so glamorous grind and predictable monotony of daily training, I'm ready for the uncertainty of adventure. The last 5 months, I have been so focused on getting in all the mileage and all the workouts while balancing work, and now it's finally time to rest. This month I'll be racing the Lavaredo 80km (@lavaredoultratrail) and fastpacking the Trail Mont Blanc in five days. Anything could happen and I'm ready for it!

Leading up to the @lavaredoultratrail 80k on Saturday, I am participating in the 2023 La Sportiva International Athlete Meeting. What a joy to share a meal with fellow Italian, Australian, New Zealand, UK and Spanish teammates in the most beautiful place. 

Grateful to make new friends (@ire.santo, @_gloriarobuschi_, @mickeygraglia, @silvia_cortesi, @nicgiovanelli, @sophieamygrant, @patripinedacornejo, @kel.lupo, @do_your_impossible) and hangout with old friends (@aaroncknight, @ale_tedoldi).
I didn't have much time to preview the @lavaredoultratrail 80k course, but from what I did see it's going to be a hot wild ride around the mountain!

A big turn out for the @lasportivagram community run! Athletes from all over the world had the opportunity to try out La Sportivas and we ran together up to a beautiful lake. Thanks to @ale_tedoldi for organizing! 

Great to see @antonkrupicka again and spend time with @kel.lupo before she takes on the 120k tonight at 11pm local time. Follow @lasportivagram for cool videos on their stories this whole race weekend.

social_posts.post_text:
Nothing left to do but run. The fun starts Saturday morning at 7am local time (1am eastern and 10pm pacific Friday night). There is live tracking at https://lavaredo.livetrail.net or you can follow my Instagram stories for the critically acclaimed "Tad Takeover." Coverage starts when Tad feels like it 😄
Thank you for all the love and support; I definitely feel it when I'm out there ♥️

Racing the Lavaredo 80K was an unforgettable experience and one I am still processing. It was the most stunning scenery I have ever seen; nothing compares to the dolomiti landscape.

Lavaredo has a reputation in the US as being a really technical and challenging race. Rather than let that intimidate me, I trusted my Italian blood to help me. Cortina lies in the Belluno region, which is where my great-grandparents are from, so a part of me felt at home right from the start.

A couple weeks leading up to the race, I had a couple sore spots in my ankle and plantar that forced more rest than usual before a race. The first major downhill I tripped and rolled, aggravating my already sore tendon, but luckily, it didn't get worse. The extended taper proved to be beneficial because my legs felt super strong from start to finish, and I managed the heat and altitude without any problems. 

I had the joy and privilege of sharing miles with  @woodside.adventures and watching her bomb the technical downhills while I carefully picked my way down.

I am incredibly grateful for the La Sportiva family for their support and kinship this week. Thank you all for your loving and supportive messages. And thank you to Tad for, well, everything.  If you missed his "Tad Takeover," you can find it saved in my profile stories under "Lavaredo 80k '23." He is going to put together a video with the gopro footage that I am excited to share with you on how I got to my 7th place finish.

I'm really proud of this one. For 18 months I put in consistent blocks of 90+ mile weeks and long 18-20 mile tempo runs with solid elevation gain. It finally paid off and it feels good.

 #lavaredoultratrail #lasportiva #foryourmountain

A lot went right the past three weeks, which isn't always the case when you plan a big trip to Europe. I got to spend a week with the international @lasportivagram team, I had the best European race of my career with a top ten finish @lavaredoultratrail 80k, I got to see my family in Italy, and Tad and I went on a 5 day trek around Mont Blanc and are still happily married. That's not to say nothing went wrong (my phone died, and I lost two years' worth of photos, and someone ran into our rental car while parked). I'm leaving here feeling overwhelmed with gratitude for this experience.

Getting back into a routine takes a little time after three weeks off of work and training. It's fun and exciting for every day to be different and unpredictable. I am consciously and intentionally settling into my days as I switch focus back on my clients, reconnecting with them and continuing to learn while starting a new training block.
Starting a shorter training block before heading back to race CCC 100k.
What good is living the life you've been given if all you do is stand in one place?
Last weekend we explored parts of the Pacific Crest Trail we haven't seen before. Just me, Tad, and every mosquito in the PNW.

Last year for CCC I did not use poles. It's hard for me to eat and drink enough when they're in my hands. After doing the trek around Mont Blanc in June, I decided that having them with me this year would be more beneficial than not having them, especially for the final climb and descent in the dark. So in preparation I've been eating, drinking, running, carrying, stashing - pretty much everything but sleeping with them (though there have been a couple days where I definitely could have curled up with them on the side of the trail).

The topic of mortality has come up a lot during sessions this week. Seeing the transient nature of our humanness through aging parents, aging bodies, or losing a loved one can bring up a lot of fear, naturally so. We can't control the inevitability of loss so we clamp down on what we can, and in this case in the form of food or body control. The irony is that being paralyzed by fear stops us from truly living. Acceptance of reality is super hard (and takes time!), but with it comes the freedom to live fully.
If you ever need a break from the sun go to Opal Cone. The sun is guaranteed to never be out.

Two weeks until race day! I cut back my mileage significantly before @lavaredoultratrail and that seemed to work so I'm doing a version of that before the @utmbmontblanc CCC, but keeping the weekly workouts.

I've been mentally preparing and visualizing the final climb in CCC and this morning I got an email  that the course changed and we won't be doing the gnarly climb up Tête aux Vents in the dark. The reroute to Flégère is part of the old Mont Blanc Marathon course I did in 2017. Just one of - I'm sure - many adjustments I'll need to accept as I make my way to Chamonix.
A touch of turnover before race day. Mid-30's this time  of year is wild, but it looks like the torrential rains are over and it's going to warm up for the race Friday, thankfully!

This might sound crazy, but I want to take an hour off my @utmbmontblanc CCC time from last year. Last year I went into CCC with it being my first 100k, having never raced in the dark or with that much elevation gain. I was running to get the experience and finish. I ended up running solid the whole way, which was great, but not really racing or pushing it. If you watch Tad's takeover saved in my profile from last year, you see I'm making jokes and taking my sweet time. I spent 16 minutes in the aid stations -- versus the 5 minutes I just spent at the @lavaredoultratrail 80k.

I put all of my focus and attention this year on having a good race at Lavaredo in June so CCC feels like a bonus gift, an opportunity to go for it with nothing to lose. I'm going into tomorrow with more experience and more confidence at the distance. I'm not going to be running stupid, but I'm going to be running with more intensity to put myself where I "should" be in this field. 

The race starts Friday at 9am local time/12:00am Pacific/3:00am Eastern with the Tad Takeover beginning shortly before. You can follow my dot at https://live.utmb.world/utmb/2023/ccc.

As usual, thank you for the love and support. I feel it all.

I've spent the past two days sitting in the expected waves of emotion that come with a DNF. I have bounced around from feeling grief for not having the performance I dreamed of, shame for my body not being able to continue on one of the grandest stages, and being embarrassed for spending so much time and money to come back to Europe again this summer. I felt greedy and foolish to have asked so much of myself.

When @courtneydauwalter was asked her Why after winning UTMB, she said, "Anytime we're given the opportunity to try something difficult or crazy, we should absolutely take it." Eight weeks ago I ran the best ultra of my life at Lavaredo and was presented with this opportunity to come back and run at the greatest ultra event in the world. I wanted to try. I was on a high from my 7th place finish and thought I could do anything. Looking back, I did not take the time needed to recover fully from that race. Three days later I trekked the 106 mile Trail Mont Blanc and then came home and got right back into training with barely one week off because I didn't have a lot of time before leaving again. While my workouts went well, looking back, there were hints my body was giving me that fatigue was setting in. 

Right from the start of CCC, things felt off. My heart rate skyrocketed and I could not get it to calm despite slowing down and taking deep breaths.This made it really difficult to eat enough, but I stayed positive and patient to wait for things to change. My legs and arms felt so weak. When my head started pounding, I was more scared than anything going up Grand Col Ferret that something was wrong. I didn't want to push my body through another 14 hours of this for no reason. My clients and I talk all the time about ways your body says no. My body was clearly saying no and I needed to listen. Walking to Chamonix seemed pointless, and quite frankly, dreadful. DNFing also sucks, but a wise friend told me that DNF stands for "Did Nothing Foolish." I went, I tried, I didn't conquer. That's okay. 

(Continued in comments.)

What gets me out the door?

I could say it's because I've been running since I was ten years old and the routine of moving my body each day is all I've ever known. But that's not the only reason. 

I run because it brings me into greater alignment with my core values of authenticity, vulnerability and connection. 

I feel most myself when in a running kit. When I'm out running alone for hours, I have a lot of time to figure out who I want to be and how I want to be in the world. It's hard to hide from my emotions when I'm running and the rhythm of my feet and breath help me move through the feelings. Running challenges me to stand up to my fears and catch myself when I inevitably fall. Running connects me to nature, a need I have every day, and it connects me to people all over the world, which is the greatest gift of all. 

@rei x @runjanji x @lasportivana #DoortoWorld
While I embrace The Big Rest of 2023, here is a little jaunt Tad and I took last week up the Grand Muveran. An early start meant we shared the trail with just the Chamois and Ibex.

The bird doesn't land on the branch because it thinks it won't break. The bird lands on the branch because it knows it can fly. 

In other words

I'm still going to be okay even if I fail, even if I make a mistake, even if this person lets me down, even if I DNF, even if I feel discomfort

Because I'm competent and capable and compassionate. 

And so are you.

The first mountain run with my nephews on Mt Baker was really special. I couldn't have asked for a more beautiful day to share this  important part of me. The funny thing was before we even started the run, I busted my knee and Tad fell over a tree stump. At the end of the video, you'll see both boys trip and we cheer that now we all did it. I wanted to normalize falling so they wouldn't be embarrassed about it and it's all part of the experience. I hope this is something we can continue to do together as they get older.
These mountain days are winding down. Every time we can get out is a gift.
Larch Madness - Day 1: Maple Pass
Larch Madness - Day 2: Harts Pass
Larch Madness - Day 3: Cutthroat Pass

You'll forget the sun in his jealous sky as we walk in fields of gold. 

The golden larch needles have been fully aflame in the alpine. It's a stunning send off before the dark rainy months ahead. Nature is neat.

Today is world mental health day. Mental health is often talked about as a separate entity from physical or bodily health. Among the messages of awareness and advocacy, I want to add that there is no disconnect between mental health and physical health because your mind and body are the same system. When I am in a dysregulated state I feel it all over - a tightness in my chest, an anvil in my stomach, dull aching in my hands. Taking care of your mental health is taking care of your physical health. 

Holding space for those that need it. 

#WorldMentalHealthDay

Fat is not a feeling, what are you really feeling? How do you know you overate if you don't know what enough feels like? What makes someone or something healthy? How would you know inside that everybody is judging you?

These are all some tough questions that we got curious about in sessions this week. Getting clarity is not always easy, but so necessary for getting unstuck.

And if you follow your feelings
And you follow your dreams
You might find the forest there in the trees.

Happy birthday, Tom ❤️
@tompettyofficial

Self-reflection is hard. It's hard to hold yourself in warm regard while acknowledging you are a flawed human being. It's hard to give yourself loving kindness while accepting your faults. It's hard to offer yourself compassion when the swamp of shame is so deep. Self-reflection is hard.

The running part of me has been quieter lately while I work. Work with my clients, work in personal relationships, work on myself. I've opened up more session slots on my calendar to accommodate for Diet Culture Season. It's a hard time of year for a lot of people and if you find yourself needing some extra support, please don't hesitate to reach out.

In the past, I've had so much anxiety and panic that I could not run alone in our local mountains. It's not like I was scared of anything real, but I was scared of being scared. My irrational fear was more scary than the thought of encountering a mountain lion or human predator. I've done a lot of work around this anxiety - none easy - and it has resulted in a complete 180. Now, I cherish my alone time in the woods. Chuckanut Mountain is my refuge, my safe place, my sanctuary. I go there to breathe, to connect, to be myself. Words can't adequately express how freeing this feels.
A sincere expression of gratitude to my clients both past and present. Thank you for teaching me, for challenging me and for trusting me to be alongside you.

During my client group session we talked a lot about using running as a coping mechanism. How do we know when the thing we love that makes us feel connected,  authentic and present is being used to avoid, numb, punish or for temporary safety? Do we need running to feel ok about ourselves or ok in our bodies? Or do we want to run because it brings us closer to living in alignment with our values?

Full reel this time 🤦🏻‍♀️
Abundance this time of year can be scary and intimidating for people who have challenges around food. I'm curious, what if we reframe abundance as enoughness? When you are so familiar with not having enough, having enough can feel like too much and therefore really uncomfortable. This overwhelm can feel like an urge to eat everything or save everything or, on the contrary, not have anything at all because you don't know when to stop. Sending lots of compassion to those grappling with abundance and scarcity this time of year.

If you want me to share more of what I'm thinking about or working on in sessions, let me know and I can do more of these little videos.

My big race for 2024 is the @lavaredoultratrail 120k (75 miles)! I'm excited to go back to Cortina next June, but this time for the long event. I had a really positive experience racing the 80k so am ready to see what this new distance has in store. The 120k starts at 11:00pm and I am dreaming of seeing the famous Tre Cime di Lavaredo at sunrise.

Walk slowly, go farther.  

This may seem like common sense when it comes to long distance running. To cover many miles you have to approach the course before you with patience, pacing and problem solving. Going out too hard, too fast, too soon can lead to burnout, sickness or stuckness. 

This approach is not unlike the work I do with clients. It's not a program where 'in 8 weeks you're going to have a "healthier" relationship with food and your body.' The amount of time it takes is going to depend on how much safety, skills, tools and resources each person needs in order to do hard things that actually foster growth. We can only go as fast as the slowest parts of you. 

To schedule a free discovery call with me please visit https://www.mariadalzotrd.com/schedule.
No pithy reflection to start the new year. 2024, let's do this 🤘
